/*
 * STAGING — Mali-G57 GPU DVFS (devfreq) OPP table. Optional, off the critical path.
 *
 * GATED on an upstream clock fix (this was previously — wrongly — believed free-
 * standing). The A523/T527 GPU mod clock (0x670) is a CYCLE-MASKING / fractional
 * divider: rate = source * (16 - M) / 16, NOT a linear M+1 divider. Mainline still
 * models it as linear, so every OPP needing M>0 SILENTLY OVERCLOCKS the Mali: on
 * hardware "150 MHz" runs at ~487 MHz, "200"->648, "300"->560, "400"->750 (25% over
 * the vendor ceiling — thermal throttling to "400" actually RAISES the clock).
 * Measured by Juan Manuel Lopez Carrillo (ut-slayer) on an OrangePi 4A with the Mali
 * cycle counter; the fractional model was confirmed by Chen-Yu Tsai.
 *   -> DO NOT enable this table until the fix lands. His series "clk: sunxi-ng: fix
 *      the A523/T527 GPU clock model, enable GPU DVFS" (linux-sunxi, v1 2026-07-19:
 *      adds a ccu_maskdiv clock type + switches the A523 gpu_clk to it + drops the
 *      pll-periph0-800M parent + parks the GPU on 600M during pll-gpu changes) is in
 *      review and mainline-bound. Once it merges, a kernel rebase makes gpu_clk
 *      correct and this table safe. Track it; do NOT carry the in-review v1 here.
 *   -> Only 200/300/400/600 MHz map to M=0 (exact under either model). 150 MHz and
 *      every turbo row below are wrong until the maskdiv fix (see the ceiling note).
 * HW-UNVERIFIED regardless. To use (POST-fix): #include from the board DTS after the
 * &gpu enable, or paste these nodes in.
 *
 * Frequencies = the VENDOR DTB `gpu-opp-table` (full 10-step ladder), confirmed
 * from the stock firmware. The vendor board DTB is BYTE-IDENTICAL between fw
 * v1.0.1 and v1.0.2 (md5 967f1c68…), so this table is current and authoritative.
 *   150 / 200 / 300 / 400 / 600 / 648 / 696 / 744 / 840 / 888 MHz.
 * (The earlier draft stopped at 600 MHz; the vendor ladder actually tops out at
 * 888 MHz. Vendor per-step microvolts run 900–1050 mV — see the comment below on
 * why they are NOT reproduced here.)
 *
 * Voltage is intentionally NOT scaled (clock-only OPP, no opp-microvolt):
 * mali-supply is AXP2202 dcdc2, a SHARED, regulator-always-on GPU+VE rail
 * (board DTS pins it at 920 mV). Per docs/GPU-NOTES.md it must be treated as a
 * static system rail, so Panfrost devfreq scales CLK_GPU ("core") only.
 *   -> IF the OPP core rejects this because mali-supply is bound, add an
 *      identical `opp-microvolt = <920000>;` to every row (a no-op on the fixed
 *      always-on rail — must match reg_dcdc2's constraint, NOT a lower value).
 *   -> Only add real per-step voltages if the GPU ever gets its own rail. The
 *      vendor voltages (for reference, if a dedicated rail appears) are:
 *      150–648 MHz @ 900 mV, 696 @ 920, 744/840 @ 1000, 888 @ 1050.
 *
 * HW-verify: that CLK_GPU actually reaches each rate — this is exactly the linear-
 * vs-masking bug above — and that the top rates are stable on the device. The 648+
 * MHz entries are the vendor "turbo"/speed-bin steps: they run from pll-gpu (a live
 * variable PLL, SID-efuse gated), which Juan's first series deliberately DEFERS to a
 * follow-up, so they are DOUBLY gated (maskdiv fix + the pll-gpu speed-bin work).
 * Keep the default ceiling conservative (600 MHz, the top M=0 universal rate) and
 * only raise it after both land + on-device thermal/stability testing on the fixed rail.
 */

&gpu {
	operating-points-v2 = <&gpu_opp_table>;
};

/ {
	gpu_opp_table: opp-table-gpu {
		compatible = "operating-points-v2";

		opp-150000000 {
			opp-hz = /bits/ 64 <150000000>;
		};
		opp-200000000 {
			opp-hz = /bits/ 64 <200000000>;
		};
		opp-300000000 {
			opp-hz = /bits/ 64 <300000000>;
		};
		opp-400000000 {
			opp-hz = /bits/ 64 <400000000>;
		};
		opp-600000000 {
			opp-hz = /bits/ 64 <600000000>;
		};
		opp-648000000 {
			opp-hz = /bits/ 64 <648000000>;
		};
		opp-696000000 {
			opp-hz = /bits/ 64 <696000000>;
		};
		opp-744000000 {
			opp-hz = /bits/ 64 <744000000>;
		};
		opp-840000000 {
			opp-hz = /bits/ 64 <840000000>;
		};
		opp-888000000 {
			opp-hz = /bits/ 64 <888000000>;
		};
	};
};
